s they pose, and how democracies should respond.Spin Dictators traces how leaders such as Singapore’s Lee Kuan Yew and Peru’s Alberto Fujimori pioneered less violent, more covert, and more effective methods of monopolizing power. They cultivated an image of competence, concealed censorship, and used democratic institutions to undermine democracy, all while increasing international engagement for financial and reputational benefits. The book reveals why most of today’s authoritarians are spin dictators—and how they differ from the remaining “fear dictators” such as Kim Jong-un and Bashar al-Assad, as well as from masters of high-tech repression like Xi Jinping.Offering incisive portraits of today’s authoritarian leaders, Spin Dictators explains some of the great political puzzles of our time—from how dictators can survive in an age of growing modernity to the disturbing convergence and mutual sympathy between dictators and populists like Donald Trump.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAuthoritarianism2DLC. 0aAuthoritarianism. 0aDictators2DLC. 0aDictators. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects2DLC. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aPropaganda2DLC. 0aPropaganda. 0aSpin doctors2DLC. 0aSpin doctors. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Fascism & Totalitarianism.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAlberto Fujimori.  aAmnesty International.  aAnimal Farm.  aAntónio de Oliveira Salazar.  aAppellate Body.  aAristocracy.  aAuthoritarianism.  aAutocracy.  aAyatollah.  aBallot.  aBeijing.  aBersih.  aBill Clinton.  aBurberry.  aCensorship.  aCommunism.  aCommunist state.  aCorruption.  aCurrency.  aDebt.  aDictatorship.  aDisinformation.  aDissident.  aEconomic development.  aEconomy of the Soviet Union.  aEl Comercio (Peru).  aElectronic media.  aEnlace.  aE